1
00:00:36,369 --> 00:00:37,746
{\an8}Ouch!

2
00:00:38,788 --> 00:00:39,914
{\an8}I can’t breathe!

3
00:00:40,915 --> 00:00:43,835
{\an8}Mom!

4
00:01:17,827 --> 00:01:19,704
{\an8}We’re not underestimating you.

5
00:01:24,083 --> 00:01:26,544
{\an8}Because we are willing
to cooperate with you.

6
00:01:27,295 --> 00:01:29,297
{\an8}And I hope you too.

7
00:01:54,781 --> 00:01:58,910
{\an8}I guess I was just trying
to get close to you all.

8
00:02:06,126 --> 00:02:07,252
{\an8}That's pretty rare.

9
00:02:10,547 --> 00:02:14,467
{\an8}I'm not the kind of senator
who's driven by ego,

10
00:02:14,551 --> 00:02:16,970
{\an8}who refuses to apologize
when they make a mistake.

11
00:02:17,554 --> 00:02:19,514
{\an8}Instead of saying sorry,

12
00:02:20,098 --> 00:02:21,808
{\an8}they even gaslight people.

13
00:02:28,815 --> 00:02:30,150
{\an8}There!

14
00:02:30,233 --> 00:02:32,402
{\an8}We're all friends again.

15
00:02:32,485 --> 00:02:34,571
{\an8}Now we can finally start the real meeting.

16
00:02:42,162 --> 00:02:44,581
{\an8}What exactly is this Concordat?

17
00:02:56,175 --> 00:02:59,512
{\an8}The Concordat began in the 1900s.

18
00:03:17,405 --> 00:03:20,992
{\an8}<i>It's an organization</i>
<i>similar to the European Union.</i>

19
00:03:21,075 --> 00:03:24,954
{\an8}<i>Like the United Nations,</i>
<i>but for criminals.</i>

20
00:03:44,390 --> 00:03:47,393
<i>But since the Concordat</i>
<i>was created not for peace,</i>

21
00:03:47,477 --> 00:03:48,728
<i>but for chaos,</i>

22
00:03:48,811 --> 00:03:51,231
<i>the unity of nations</i>

23
00:03:51,314 --> 00:03:54,317
<i>became the greatest threat to its power.</i>

24
00:04:55,336 --> 00:04:58,506
AMERICA: UNDER ATTACK AND WAR

25
00:05:08,266 --> 00:05:11,227
Are you saying she's planning
to cause chaos here in the Philippines?

26
00:05:11,311 --> 00:05:13,271
Not just in the Philippines,

27
00:05:14,063 --> 00:05:16,357
but throughout the world.

28
00:05:16,941 --> 00:05:20,111
And here in the Philippines
lies her means to bring havoc

29
00:05:20,194 --> 00:05:21,612
to the whole world.

30
00:05:21,696 --> 00:05:23,072
How?

31
00:05:27,994 --> 00:05:29,078
What's Broken Arrow?

32
00:05:29,162 --> 00:05:31,164
I have broken vows.

33
00:05:31,706 --> 00:05:33,082
What's Broken Arrow?

34
00:05:42,967 --> 00:05:47,680
The Broken Arrow refers to an incident
that happened in 1965.

35
00:05:47,764 --> 00:05:50,558
<i>It involved an American fighter jet</i>

36
00:05:50,641 --> 00:05:54,771
<i>that crashed into the Philippine Sea</i>
<i>somewhere near the Batanes Islands.</i>

37
00:06:07,200 --> 00:06:11,746
Neither was the nuclear bomb
it was carrying.

38
00:06:11,829 --> 00:06:17,126
And that is why the Philippines
is very important to the mafia,

39
00:06:17,210 --> 00:06:20,088
because in this country lies the weapon

40
00:06:20,171 --> 00:06:24,300
that could bring chaos
and instability to the entire world.

41
00:06:24,383 --> 00:06:27,762
But no one has recovered
that weapon, right?

42
00:06:27,845 --> 00:06:34,018
Like you said, it sank
into the depths of the ocean, correct?

43
00:06:50,743 --> 00:06:52,620
What’s happening?

44
00:06:53,496 --> 00:06:54,997
They seem to be feeling faint.

45
00:06:55,081 --> 00:06:55,998
Let’s check them.

46
00:07:01,629 --> 00:07:03,297
- Go, ask for help!
- All right, okay!

47
00:07:03,381 --> 00:07:05,007
Help! Help!

48
00:07:11,848 --> 00:07:13,433
Help!

49
00:07:13,516 --> 00:07:16,394
Are you saying that someone
already recovered the bomb?

50
00:07:17,353 --> 00:07:19,063
Based on the information I have,

51
00:07:19,147 --> 00:07:21,983
it was accidentally caught by a fisherman,

52
00:07:22,066 --> 00:07:24,318
who later died from exposure.

53
00:07:24,402 --> 00:07:25,570
Wait.

54
00:07:25,653 --> 00:07:29,073
Why wasn't this incident reported?

55
00:07:29,657 --> 00:07:32,869
Actually, it seems that it was reported.

56
00:07:34,537 --> 00:07:38,207
<i>A college professor named Enrico Santos…</i>

57
00:07:43,296 --> 00:07:46,007
<i>…but he vanished and disappeared.</i>

58
00:07:49,385 --> 00:07:50,845
<i>So how did you know all of this?</i>

59
00:07:50,928 --> 00:07:53,014
How did the mafia learn about it?

60
00:07:55,725 --> 00:07:58,311
From what I know, this professor
fell victim to a phishing scam

61
00:07:58,394 --> 00:08:01,481
because he liked dating sites.

62
00:08:04,692 --> 00:08:06,736
And in one of his emails,

63
00:08:06,819 --> 00:08:09,363
he described a radioactive bomb

64
00:08:09,447 --> 00:08:12,783
that he stumbled upon during one
of his community outreach programs.

65
00:08:13,868 --> 00:08:17,079
He knew the value of that information,

66
00:08:17,163 --> 00:08:19,040
so he hid it,

67
00:08:19,123 --> 00:08:22,126
planning to sell it someday
to the highest bidder.

68
00:08:34,764 --> 00:08:39,143
What matters is that it's
a very, very powerful weapon.

69
00:08:39,227 --> 00:08:41,729
And if it falls
into the Concordat's hands,

70
00:08:41,812 --> 00:08:46,317
they will have the capability
to bring chaos to the world.

71
00:09:08,798 --> 00:09:11,467
Tens of thousands
will be killed or injured,

72
00:09:12,218 --> 00:09:15,012
with millions more affected
by the nuclear fallout.

73
00:09:21,102 --> 00:09:22,311
‪Oh, so…

74
00:09:23,521 --> 00:09:26,107
Do you have any idea
where this weapon might be now?

75
00:09:29,110 --> 00:09:32,113
That's where the college professor
was last seen before he disappeared.

76
00:09:41,038 --> 00:09:43,708
But maybe there's
a digital footprint we can use

77
00:09:43,791 --> 00:09:45,334
to find that professor?

78
00:09:46,252 --> 00:09:47,420
There's no trace of him.

79
00:09:50,965 --> 00:09:53,801
That's why La Morte Bianca
wants to control the world,

80
00:09:53,884 --> 00:09:55,636
and that's what the Moravianos are doing.

81
00:10:08,232 --> 00:10:10,901
And I no longer have any information
about their plans or movements.

82
00:10:11,777 --> 00:10:13,279
All I know is,

83
00:10:13,362 --> 00:10:16,490
La Morte Bianca is already
here in the Philippines,

84
00:10:17,116 --> 00:10:22,747
and I'm sure she will utilize everything
just to find that college professor.

85
00:11:08,959 --> 00:11:10,252
Bye.

86
00:11:17,593 --> 00:11:21,680
If we have the same information
as the Concordat has,

87
00:11:22,515 --> 00:11:25,351
what advantage do we have
over them at this point?

88
00:11:37,279 --> 00:11:39,824
That's my great love! So feisty!

89
00:12:25,786 --> 00:12:29,457
We need to stop La Morte Bianca

90
00:12:30,166 --> 00:12:32,251
before she gets her hands on that bomb.

91
00:12:45,473 --> 00:12:49,310
I want eyes and ears
in every part of the Philippines.

92
00:13:32,269 --> 00:13:36,148
Okay, I'm assigning Ben
to stay with you guys

93
00:13:36,232 --> 00:13:39,527
because I know he can watch
over both of you.

94
00:13:40,528 --> 00:13:43,405
There shouldn't be any problem
with you staying under one roof.

95
00:13:46,825 --> 00:13:47,785
How about you?

96
00:13:47,868 --> 00:13:50,496
Maybe you should ask the two of them first

97
00:13:50,579 --> 00:13:53,374
if they even want you
living under the same roof.

98
00:13:53,874 --> 00:13:55,042
Maybe they don't.

99
00:14:08,597 --> 00:14:12,893
Because we don't really need
Agent Alex's protection.

100
00:14:13,852 --> 00:14:17,147
Mikoy and I managed on our own
back in Hong Kong.

101
00:14:18,983 --> 00:14:20,401
We can do it again.

102
00:14:24,530 --> 00:14:25,906
Chiara's pretending,

103
00:14:25,990 --> 00:14:29,660
but she's clearly falling for my charm.

104
00:14:31,537 --> 00:14:34,915
I told you, I'm so magnetic.

105
00:14:36,750 --> 00:14:38,419
Like a refrigerator magnet.

106
00:14:40,880 --> 00:14:41,797
Jealous.

107
00:14:41,881 --> 00:14:43,674
That's because you have no love life.

108
00:14:46,051 --> 00:14:49,263
Okay, well, the meeting's over now, right?

109
00:14:57,563 --> 00:15:02,151
I need to go to the nail salon,
and I need a massage.

110
00:15:02,735 --> 00:15:05,863
I got a stiff neck
because you put me in a coffin, right?

111
00:15:14,955 --> 00:15:17,458
What, are you keeping us
as prisoners here?

112
00:15:34,308 --> 00:15:36,852
I don't understand why you're surprised.

113
00:15:36,936 --> 00:15:38,145
This was the deal.

114
00:15:39,730 --> 00:15:41,565
This was not part of the deal.

115
00:15:46,820 --> 00:15:49,281
We have lives and families.

116
00:15:57,373 --> 00:16:01,460
We asked for immunity in exchange
for the information I gave earlier.

117
00:16:06,799 --> 00:16:12,304
We are doing this to first verify
the information you gave us.

118
00:16:12,388 --> 00:16:16,141
We still don't have
mutual trust in each other.

119
00:16:24,775 --> 00:16:26,568
Why? This place is fine.

120
00:16:27,152 --> 00:16:29,029
You have plenty of room to move around.

121
00:16:29,863 --> 00:16:31,115
I understand, sir.

122
00:16:31,198 --> 00:16:34,159
Actually, whatever the agency wants
is fine with me.

123
00:16:34,243 --> 00:16:35,160
We're okay with it.

124
00:16:35,995 --> 00:16:40,290
I just hope there's a swimming pool
to cool off our hot heads.

125
00:16:54,013 --> 00:16:55,431
What am I supposed to do now?

126
00:16:56,932 --> 00:16:58,976
Well, you've already completed
one day of internship?

127
00:17:00,185 --> 00:17:02,980
Basically, you'll just keep doing
what you've been doing.

128
00:17:03,731 --> 00:17:06,150
What, put boxes on the motorcycle again?

129
00:17:06,233 --> 00:17:07,401
I don't want that anymore.

130
00:17:07,484 --> 00:17:08,902
I want the hard part.

131
00:17:08,986 --> 00:17:12,489
I want to experience
baking a torta. Come on.

132
00:17:12,573 --> 00:17:14,324
It will be our baby.

133
00:17:15,034 --> 00:17:16,702
What baby are you talking about?

134
00:17:17,327 --> 00:17:19,872
Our torta baby. That's what I meant.

135
00:17:19,955 --> 00:17:22,458
Come on. We're going to make it together.

136
00:17:22,541 --> 00:17:24,418
I don't know what kind of terms
you're learning these days.

137
00:17:24,501 --> 00:17:25,753
That's from being on your phone too much.

138
00:17:25,836 --> 00:17:27,421
Come on, teach me.

139
00:17:28,047 --> 00:17:29,256
No, I can't.

140
00:17:29,339 --> 00:17:30,424
We have too many orders.

141
00:17:30,507 --> 00:17:32,551
I don't have time for lessons right now.

142
00:17:32,634 --> 00:17:34,219
Please, just one?

143
00:17:38,057 --> 00:17:39,600
Do you want me to kneel here?

144
00:17:39,683 --> 00:17:40,809
Do whatever you want.

145
00:17:41,727 --> 00:17:43,437
I'm really going to kneel. Here I go.

146
00:17:43,520 --> 00:17:45,147
Sofie, what are you doing?

147
00:17:45,230 --> 00:17:48,275
You're wearing shorts.
What if you get hurt?

148
00:17:48,358 --> 00:17:49,777
You won't teach me.

149
00:17:49,860 --> 00:17:51,195
You're so persistent, Sofie.

150
00:17:51,278 --> 00:17:53,822
Fine then, sift this, this dry mixture,

151
00:17:53,906 --> 00:17:55,449
so we can finish faster.

152
00:17:56,492 --> 00:17:57,367
Here.

153
00:17:59,745 --> 00:18:00,996
Not like that!

154
00:18:01,080 --> 00:18:02,331
- Why?
- That's wrong.

155
00:18:02,414 --> 00:18:03,457
You told me to sift it.

156
00:18:03,540 --> 00:18:05,959
Like this. There, this one, like this.

157
00:18:06,043 --> 00:18:07,419
But hold it more gently.

158
00:18:07,503 --> 00:18:09,296
Don't grip it too hard.

159
00:18:09,379 --> 00:18:12,382
Then, there, go ahead. Put it in.

160
00:18:13,425 --> 00:18:16,261
That's it. Now slowly. Okay.

161
00:18:35,322 --> 00:18:38,408
So finally, we're going to bake our baby!

162
00:18:41,829 --> 00:18:43,914
Will you stop calling it a baby?

163
00:18:43,997 --> 00:18:47,459
If Mom and Dad hear you,
they'll get the wrong idea.

164
00:18:50,462 --> 00:18:51,588
So?

165
00:18:51,672 --> 00:18:53,507
Come on. Help me with this.

166
00:18:54,633 --> 00:18:56,760
Didn't you say it was too heavy
for you the first time?

167
00:18:56,844 --> 00:18:57,886
I've got it.

168
00:18:58,470 --> 00:19:01,056
Or we can do it together.

169
00:19:02,307 --> 00:19:03,142
Okay.

170
00:19:06,562 --> 00:19:08,564
Oh, for heaven's sake!

171
00:19:08,647 --> 00:19:11,942
We have so much to prepare,
and all you do is fool around?

172
00:19:12,025 --> 00:19:13,902
I’m telling this to Miss Tess.

173
00:19:14,486 --> 00:19:16,280
You're the one who hasn't been here.

174
00:19:16,363 --> 00:19:17,447
Me?

175
00:19:17,531 --> 00:19:19,992
Sorry, okay? I'm here now.

176
00:19:20,701 --> 00:19:22,828
What else is missing? I'll do it.

177
00:19:22,911 --> 00:19:25,080
Here. This one.

178
00:19:26,331 --> 00:19:27,958
Miss Betchay, come on.

179
00:19:28,458 --> 00:19:30,335
- Teach me how to do it.
- Go ahead and pour that for me.

180
00:19:30,419 --> 00:19:31,461
- Let's mix it.
- Pour it like this?

181
00:19:31,545 --> 00:19:33,005
Mix.

182
00:19:33,589 --> 00:19:35,215
- Then what?
- Go ahead.

183
00:19:46,727 --> 00:19:51,106
I need to inform the President about
this radioactive material in our country.

184
00:19:51,857 --> 00:19:54,234
Because we're not dealing
with a crime syndicate.

185
00:19:58,113 --> 00:20:01,658
We have to verify and cross-check

186
00:20:01,742 --> 00:20:04,286
all the information
Chiara gave us earlier first.

187
00:20:04,870 --> 00:20:08,582
We need to know for sure
whether that bomb really exists.

188
00:20:09,541 --> 00:20:12,878
What if Chiara is just
pulling the wool over our eyes?

189
00:20:14,296 --> 00:20:16,006
Pulling the wool over my eyes?
I'm already bald.

190
00:20:18,217 --> 00:20:19,134
No.

191
00:20:19,218 --> 00:20:21,595
I'm not laughing because I'm bald.

192
00:20:22,095 --> 00:20:24,223
I'm laughing at everything
that's happening to us.

193
00:20:24,306 --> 00:20:27,559
There's a nuclear or chemical bomb
we need to find.

194
00:20:27,643 --> 00:20:30,479
What if we end up finding
the Sex Bomb Girls instead?

195
00:20:32,397 --> 00:20:34,983
- Oh my God.
- But you're right, comrade.

196
00:20:35,734 --> 00:20:39,613
Every day I pray that
none of this would happen.

197
00:20:41,782 --> 00:20:44,451
If there's one thing
we should be grateful for,

198
00:20:45,911 --> 00:20:49,706
it's that we can still
do something about it.

199
00:20:51,083 --> 00:20:52,834
We have to do everything we can

200
00:20:52,918 --> 00:20:57,381
to stop La Morte Bianca's plans
from succeeding.

201
00:20:57,464 --> 00:20:59,049
You're right, comrade.

202
00:20:59,591 --> 00:21:03,428
Don't worry, you'll have all my support.

203
00:21:05,097 --> 00:21:07,474
- Thank you, comrade.
- See you!

204
00:21:17,567 --> 00:21:21,446
You know, Chiara isn't the only one
who needs to chill out.

205
00:21:21,530 --> 00:21:23,365
Sir Norberto does too.

206
00:21:23,949 --> 00:21:27,160
He's just being careful.
That's why he made those decisions.

207
00:21:27,244 --> 00:21:29,079
I thought you trusted me?

208
00:21:29,705 --> 00:21:31,331
Yes, I trust you.

209
00:21:31,415 --> 00:21:33,375
But just because I trust you

210
00:21:33,458 --> 00:21:35,961
doesn't mean everyone
in the agency will too.

211
00:21:36,878 --> 00:21:39,423
Imagine all the resources
the agency had to deploy

212
00:21:39,506 --> 00:21:41,049
because of your Hong Kong stint.

213
00:21:41,758 --> 00:21:43,302
Everything could have been prevented

214
00:21:43,385 --> 00:21:45,095
if you'd gone to the agency
from the start.

215
00:21:49,433 --> 00:21:51,601
That's exactly why we did what we did.

216
00:21:51,685 --> 00:21:54,688
I don't easily place my trust
in authorities either.

217
00:21:55,314 --> 00:21:56,648
More often than not,

218
00:21:56,732 --> 00:21:59,943
there's a mole inside the agency.

219
00:22:01,069 --> 00:22:02,529
I like those.

220
00:22:02,612 --> 00:22:05,115
Women with beauty marks,
especially on the cheek.

221
00:22:06,325 --> 00:22:08,618
I don't really have a preference.
As long as she's kind,

222
00:22:08,702 --> 00:22:10,829
can cook well, and loves dogs.

223
00:22:11,496 --> 00:22:14,291
- You know--
- That's not the kind of mole I meant.

224
00:22:19,046 --> 00:22:21,006
Maybe this is the first time in history

225
00:22:21,089 --> 00:22:23,300
that there isn't a traitor
inside the agency.

226
00:22:29,347 --> 00:22:32,225
Okay, we need to take our leave.
We still have a lot to do.

227
00:22:32,309 --> 00:22:33,310
Just a reminder.

228
00:22:38,106 --> 00:22:39,316
Okay?

229
00:22:40,442 --> 00:22:41,651
Sianong.

230
00:22:49,701 --> 00:22:51,119
I'm just going to the kitchen.

231
00:22:52,204 --> 00:22:53,830
I've been thirsty for a while now.

232
00:23:03,298 --> 00:23:04,925
You know, sweetheart,

233
00:23:05,675 --> 00:23:07,636
this feels like my sister's house.

234
00:23:08,345 --> 00:23:09,888
There are cameras everywhere.

235
00:23:10,472 --> 00:23:14,101
There's only one way to find out
if this really is my sister's house,

236
00:23:14,184 --> 00:23:15,727
like you said.

237
00:23:20,857 --> 00:23:24,861
Chiara, Mikoy, please proceed
to the confession room.

238
00:23:25,487 --> 00:23:27,364
Why does that voice sound like that?
It's definitely my sister.

239
00:23:27,447 --> 00:23:28,990
You're right. Let's go.

240
00:23:33,495 --> 00:23:34,496
Sis?

241
00:23:37,040 --> 00:23:38,250
Sis?

242
00:23:40,544 --> 00:23:41,711
Sis!

243
00:23:45,423 --> 00:23:46,258
There it is!

244
00:23:47,634 --> 00:23:49,427
I knew it!

245
00:23:49,511 --> 00:23:52,806
There's really no safe place
in my sister's house.

246
00:23:58,520 --> 00:24:01,565
My whole life, I've felt
like I was trapped.

247
00:24:01,648 --> 00:24:05,610
It's like I just traded
a steel cage for a birdcage.

248
00:24:06,486 --> 00:24:08,822
We're still not free, Mikoy.

249
00:24:16,246 --> 00:24:18,790
What's your problem? Does your back itch?

250
00:24:18,874 --> 00:24:20,667
This car was just washed.

251
00:24:21,251 --> 00:24:23,670
- No, it's not that.
- Then what?

252
00:24:24,671 --> 00:24:26,840
I just have this feeling.

253
00:24:27,382 --> 00:24:30,010
I don't know, maybe I'm starting
to catch your gut feeling thing.

254
00:24:30,093 --> 00:24:31,928
What gut feeling?

255
00:24:32,429 --> 00:24:34,806
Because I feel like

256
00:24:34,890 --> 00:24:38,602
it was a mistake to leave Ben there
to watch over Mikoy and Chiara.

257
00:24:39,186 --> 00:24:41,479
Think about it, on his very first
appearance at the hospital,

258
00:24:41,563 --> 00:24:43,231
they got past him right away.

259
00:24:49,196 --> 00:24:50,113
What?

260
00:24:51,740 --> 00:24:55,285
Don't tell me, Bok, you're the one
falling for his charm now?

261
00:24:55,368 --> 00:24:57,621
Wow, for the second time around!

262
00:24:57,704 --> 00:24:58,914
Idiot.

263
00:24:58,997 --> 00:25:01,666
I'm just saying people change.

264
00:25:02,167 --> 00:25:06,004
Besides, who knows? Maybe
Senator Quintin sees something in him

265
00:25:06,087 --> 00:25:08,465
that we simply don't see.

266
00:25:13,053 --> 00:25:14,137
Wait.

267
00:25:26,024 --> 00:25:28,360
There. I covered it up.

268
00:25:29,110 --> 00:25:30,195
That should do it.

269
00:25:30,278 --> 00:25:32,864
And then we'll get scolded again.

270
00:25:33,865 --> 00:25:35,158
That's okay.

271
00:25:35,825 --> 00:25:38,328
We can't always keep conforming.

272
00:25:38,411 --> 00:25:42,123
We can rebel too, in our own little way.

273
00:25:43,166 --> 00:25:46,586
- I'm so stressed right now.
- Really?

274
00:25:48,838 --> 00:25:50,340
I have an idea.

275
00:25:51,716 --> 00:25:52,550
What is it?

276
00:26:04,354 --> 00:26:05,397
It’s Ben.

277
00:26:11,903 --> 00:26:13,321
Mikoy and Chiara are missing!

278
00:26:13,405 --> 00:26:14,447
What?

279
00:26:29,296 --> 00:26:31,589
Do you want us to put you in jail?

280
00:26:37,137 --> 00:26:39,222
I already talked to General Norberto.

281
00:26:39,306 --> 00:26:40,724
Because of what you did,

282
00:26:40,807 --> 00:26:42,767
he’ll send someone over
for you to be with.

283
00:26:42,851 --> 00:26:45,103
Someone who's not addicted
to staying up late,

284
00:26:45,186 --> 00:26:47,897
but addicted to the gym.

285
00:26:50,442 --> 00:26:51,484
Who?

